{"questionId":"27770","questionHtml":"<p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>≠</mo><mn>1</mn></math>, show that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>M1</strong></em> for attempting to use the quotient or the product rule to find&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math>.</p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>-</mo><mfenc